<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-505-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 505 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 28 1990 v24 n22 p107(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Disinfectants for disk drives. (computer viruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Garfinkel, Simson L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microcomputer-based programs that are now on the market can 'scan'for computer viruses, looking for unique sequences of machineinstructions.andP;  Actually, cautious management is the best defense.andO;Software publishers try to assure their products are free ofproblems because a virus could destroy a company's reputation.andO;Microsoft Corp begins with two computers that have never beenused.andP;  Then, engineers install new copies of the operating systemand compilers, transferring an application's source code to thecomputers over a serial line.andP;  Engineers do a byte-by-byteexamination of the two applications to see if the two areidentical.andP;  The company is experimenting with applications thatwill automatically check themselves for viruses each time they arerun.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (security measures)Microsoft Corp. (product enhancement).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Computer virusesSecurity SoftwareData SecurityComputer Virus Industry AssociationSoftware Publishers.andO;Person:    McAfee, John (employment).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>